# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: reverse-engineering-ghidra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] A **decompiler** is a computer program that translates an executable file back into high-level source code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Unlike a compiler, which converts high-level code into machine code, a decompiler performs the reverse process.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] While disassemblers translate executables into assembly language, decompilers go a step further by reconstructing the disassembly into higher-level languages like C.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Due to the one-way nature of the compilation process, decompilers usually cannot perfectly recreate the original source code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] They often produce obfuscated and less readable code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Decompilation is the process of transforming executable code into a high-level, human-readable format using a decompiler.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] This process is commonly used for tasks that involve reverse-engineering the logic behind executable code, such as recovering lost or unavailable source code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Decompilers face inherent challenges due to the loss of critical information during the compilation process, such as variable names, comments, and code structure.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Certain factors can impact the success of decompilation.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Executables containing detailed metadata, such as those used by Java and .NET, are easier to reverse-engineer because they often retain class structures, method signatures, and debugging information.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Executable files stripped of such context are far more challenging to translate into meaningful source code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Some software developers may obfuscate, pack, or encrypt parts of their executable programs, making the decompiled code much harder to interpret.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] These techniques are often done to deter reverse-engineering, making the process more difficult and time-intensive.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Decompilers can be thought of as composed of a series of phases each of which contributes specific aspects of the overall decompilation process.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The first decompilation phase loads and parses the input machine code or intermediate language program's binary file format.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] It should be able to discover basic facts about the input program, such as the architecture (Pentium, PowerPC, etc.) and the entry point.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] In many cases, it should be able to find the equivalent of the `main` function of a C program, which is the start of the **user written** code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] This excludes the runtime initialization code, which should not be decompiled if possible.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] If available the symbol tables and debug data are also loaded.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The front end may be able to identify the libraries used even if they are linked with the code, this will provide library interfaces.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] If it can determine the compiler or compilers used it may provide useful information in identifying code idioms.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The next logical phase is the disassembly of machine code instructions into a machine independent intermediate representation (IR).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Idiomatic machine code sequences are sequences of code whose combined semantics are not immediately apparent from the instructions' individual semantics.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Either as part of the disassembly phase, or as part of later analyses, these idiomatic sequences need to be translated into known equivalent IR.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Some idiomatic sequences are machine independent; some involve only one instruction.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] For example, `xor eax, eax` clears the `eax` register (sets it to zero).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] This can be implemented with a machine independent simplification rule, such as `a = 0`.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] In general, it is best to delay detection of idiomatic sequences if possible, to later stages that are less affected by instruction ordering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] For example, the instruction scheduling phase of a compiler may insert other instructions into an idiomatic sequence, or change the ordering of instructions in the sequence.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] A pattern matching process in the disassembly phase would probably not recognize the altered pattern.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Later phases group instruction expressions into more complex expressions, and modify them into a canonical (standardized) form, making it more likely that even the altered idiom will match a higher level pattern later in the decompilation.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] It is particularly important to recognize the compiler idioms for subroutine calls, exception handling, and switch statements.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Some languages also have extensive support for strings or long integers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Various program analyses can be applied to the IR.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] In particular, expression propagation combines the semantics of several instructions into more complex expressions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The resulting expression is more like high level language, and has also eliminated the use of the machine register `eax`.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Later analyses may eliminate the `ebx` register.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The places where register contents are defined and used must be traced using data flow analysis.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The same analysis can be applied to locations that are used for temporaries and local data.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] A different name can then be formed for each such connected set of value definitions and uses.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] It is possible that the same local variable location was used for more than one variable in different parts of the original program.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Even worse it is possible for the data flow analysis to identify a path whereby a value may flow between two such uses even though it would never actually happen or matter in reality.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] This may in bad cases lead to needing to define a location as a union of types.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The decompiler may allow the user to explicitly break such unnatural dependencies which will lead to clearer code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] This of course means a variable is potentially used without being initialized and so indicates a problem in the original program.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] A good machine code decompiler will perform type analysis.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Here, the way registers or memory locations are used result in constraints on the possible type of the location.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] For example, an `and` instruction implies that the operand is an integer; programs do not use such an operation on floating point values (except in special library code) or on pointers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] An `add` instruction results in three constraints, since the operands may be both integer, or one integer and one pointer (with integer and pointer results respectively; the third constraint comes from the ordering of the two operands when the types are different).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Various high level expressions can be recognized which trigger recognition of structures or arrays.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] However, it is difficult to distinguish many of the possibilities, because of the freedom that machine code or even some high level languages such as C allow with casts and pointer arithmetic.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The penultimate decompilation phase involves structuring of the IR into higher level constructs such as `while` loops and `if/then/else` conditional statements.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Unstructured code is more difficult to translate into structured code than already structured code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Solutions include replicating some code, or adding Boolean variables.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The final phase is the generation of the high level code in the back end of the decompiler.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Just as a compiler may have several back ends for generating machine code for different architectures, a decompiler may have several back ends for generating high level code in different high level languages.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Just before code generation, it may be desirable to allow an interactive editing of the IR, perhaps using some form of graphical user interface.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] This would allow the user to enter comments, and non-generic variable and function names.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] However, these are almost as easily entered in a post decompilation edit.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The user may want to change structural aspects, such as converting a `while` loop to a `for` loop.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] These are less readily modified with a simple text editor, although source code refactoring tools may assist with this process.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The user may need to enter information that failed to be identified during the type analysis phase, e.g. modifying a memory expression to an array or structure expression.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Finally, incorrect IR may need to be corrected, or changes made to cause the output code to be more readable.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Decompilers using neural networks have been developed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Such a decompiler may be trained by machine learning to improve its accuracy over time.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] The majority of computer programs are covered by copyright laws.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Although the precise scope of what is covered by copyright differs from region to region, copyright law generally provides the author (the programmer(s) or employer) with a collection of exclusive rights to the program.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] These rights include the right to make copies, including copies made into the computer’s RAM (unless creating such a copy is essential for using the program).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Since the decompilation process involves making multiple such copies, it is generally prohibited without the authorization of the copyright holder.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] However, because decompilation is often a necessary step in achieving software interoperability, copyright laws in both the United States and Europe permit decompilation to a limited extent.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] In the United States, the copyright fair use defence has been successfully invoked in decompilation cases.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Accolade*, the court held that Accolade could lawfully engage in decompilation in order to circumvent the software locking mechanism used by Sega's game consoles.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Additionally, the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (PUBLIC LAW 105–304) has proper exemptions for both Security Testing and Evaluation in §1201(i), and Reverse Engineering in §1201(f).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] In Europe, the 1991 Software Directive explicitly provides for a right to decompile in order to achieve interoperability.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] In addition, Article 6 prescribes that the information obtained through decompilation may not be used for other purposes and that it may not be given to others.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Overall, the decompilation right provided by Article 6 codifies what is claimed to be common practice in the software industry.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] Few European lawsuits are known to have emerged from the decompilation right.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] 3. illegal decompilation goes largely undetected.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/decompiler] In a report of 2000 regarding implementation of the Software Directive by the European member states, the European Commission seemed to support the second interpretation.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] A **disassembler** is a computer program that translates machine language into assembly language—the inverse operation to that of an assembler.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] The output of disassembly is typically formatted for human-readability rather than for input to an assembler, making disassemblers primarily a reverse-engineering tool.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Common uses include analyzing the output of high-level programming language compilers and their optimizations, recovering source code when the original is lost, performing malware analysis, modifying software (such as binary patching), and software cracking.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] A disassembler differs from a decompiler, which targets a high-level language rather than an assembly language.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] A fundamental method of software analysis is disassembly.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Unlike decompilers, which make attempts at recreating high-level human readable structures using binaries, disassemblers are aimed at generating a symbolic assembly, meaning it's attempting to reconstruct the assembly closest to its executions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Disassembled code is hence normally more accurate but also lower level and less abstract than decompiled code and thus it can be much more easily analyzed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Assembly language source code generally permits the use of constants and programmer comments.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] These are usually removed from the assembled machine code by the assembler.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] If so, a disassembler operating on the machine code would produce disassembly lacking these constants and comments; the disassembled output becomes more difficult for a human to interpret than the original annotated source code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Some disassemblers provide a built-in code commenting feature where the generated output is enriched with comments regarding called API functions or parameters of called functions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Some disassemblers make use of the symbolic debugging information present in object files such as ELF.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] For example, IDA allows the human user to make up mnemonic symbols for values or regions of code in an interactive session: human insight applied to the disassembly process often parallels human creativity in the code writing process.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] It is not always possible to distinguish executable code from data within a binary.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] While common executable formats, such as ELF and PE, separate code and data into distinct sections, flat binaries do not, making it unclear whether a given location contains executable instructions or non-executable data.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] This ambiguity might complicate the disassembly process.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Additionally, CPUs often allow dynamic jumps computed at runtime, which makes it impossible to identify all possible locations in the binary that might be executed as instructions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] On computer architectures with variable-width instructions, such as in many CISC architectures, more than one valid disassembly may exist for the same binary.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Disassemblers also cannot handle code that changes during execution, as static analysis cannot account for runtime modifications.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Encryption, packing, or obfuscation are often applied to computer programs, especially as part of digital rights management to deter reverse engineering and cracking.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] These techniques pose additional challenges for disassembly, as the code must first be unpacked or decrypted before meaningful analysis can begin.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Disassembly can be performed statically or dynamically.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] **Static disassembly** analyzes the binary without executing it, which enables offline inspection.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] However, static disassembly may misinterpret some operations or obfuscation.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] While both are respectively powerful, modern disassemblers often combine both approaches to improve accuracy in more complex binaries.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] A disassembler can be either stand-alone or interactive.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] A stand-alone disassembler generates an assembly language file upon execution, which can then be examined.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] In contrast, an interactive disassembler immediately reflects any changes made by the user.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] For example, if the disassembler initially treats a section of the program as data rather than code, the user can specify it as code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] The disassembled code will then be updated and displayed instantly, allowing the user to analyze it and make further changes during the same session.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Any interactive debugger will include some way of viewing the disassembly of the program being debugged.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Often, the same disassembly tool will be packaged as a standalone disassembler distributed along with the debugger.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] For example, objdump, part of GNU Binutils, is related to the interactive debugger gdb.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] A dynamic disassembler can be integrated into the output of an emulator or hypervisor to trace the real-time execution of machine instructions, displaying them line-by-line.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] In this setup, along with the disassembled machine code, the disassembler can show changes to registers, data, or other state elements (such as condition codes) caused by each instructions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] This provides powerful debugging information for problem resolution.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] However, the output size can become quite large, particularly if the tracing is active throughout the entire execution of a program.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] These features were first introduced in the early 1970s by OLIVER as part of its CICS debugging product and are now incorporated into the XPEDITER product from Compuware.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] A **length disassembler**, also known as **length disassembler engine** (**LDE**), is a tool that, given a sequence of bytes (instructions), outputs the number of bytes taken by the parsed instruction.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/disassembler] Notable open source projects for the x86 architecture include ldisasm, Tiny x86 Length Disassembler and Extended Length Disassembler Engine for x86-64.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/ghidra] Scripts to perform automated analysis with Ghidra can be written in Java or Python (via Jython).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/ghidra] Plugins adding new features to Ghidra itself can be developed using a Java-based extension framework.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/ghidra] Ghidra's existence was originally revealed to the public via Vault 7 in March 2017, but the software itself remained unavailable until its declassification and official release two years later.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/ghidra] Some comments in its source code indicate that it existed as early as 1999.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/ghidra] In June 2019, coreboot began to use Ghidra for its reverse engineering efforts on firmware-specific problems following the open source release of the Ghidra software suite.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/ghidra] Ghidra can be used as a debugger since Ghidra 10.0.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/ghidra] Ghidra's debugger supports debugging user-mode Windows programs via WinDbg, Linux programs via GDB and macOS programs via LLDB.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] In computing, **machine code** is data encoded and structured to control a computer's central processing unit (CPU) via its programmable interface.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] A computer program consists primarily of sequences of machine-code instructions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Machine code is classified as native with respect to its host CPU since it is the language that the CPU interprets directly.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Some software interpreters translate the programming language that they interpret into a virtual machine code (bytecode) and process it with a P-code machine.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] An instruction set architecture (ISA) defines the interface to a CPU and varies by groupings or families of CPU design such as x86 and ARM.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Generally, machine code compatible with one family is not with others, but there are exceptions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The VAX architecture includes optional support of the PDP-11 instruction set.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The IA-64 architecture includes optional support of the IA-32 instruction set.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] And, the PowerPC 615 can natively process both PowerPC and x86 instructions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Assembly language provides a relatively direct mapping from a human-readable source code to machine code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The assembly language source code represents numerical codes in machine code, as mnemonics and labels.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] For example, `NOP` in assembly for an x86 processor represents the x86 architecture opcode 0x90 in machine code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] While it is possible to write a program in machine code, doing so is tedious and error-prone.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Therefore, programs are usually written in assembly or, more commonly, in a high-level programming language.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] A machine instruction encodes an operation as a pattern of bits based on the specified format for the machine's instruction set.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Instruction sets differ in various ways.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Instructions of a set might all be the same length or different instructions might have different lengths; they might be smaller than, the same size as, or larger than the word size of the architecture.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The number of instructions may be relatively small or large.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Instructions may or may not have to be aligned on particular memory boundaries, such as the architecture's word boundary.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] An instruction set needs to execute the circuits of a computer's digital logic level.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] At the digital level, the program needs to control the computer's registers, bus, memory, ALU, and other hardware components.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] To control a computer's architectural features, machine instructions are created.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Determining the size of the address field is a choice between space and speed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] On some computers, the number of bits in the address field may be too small to access all of the physical memory.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Also, virtual address space needs to be considered.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Another constraint may be a limitation on the size of registers used to construct the address.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Whereas a shorter address field allows the instructions to execute more quickly, other physical properties need to be considered when designing the instruction format.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Instructions can be separated into two types: general-purpose and special-purpose.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Special-purpose instructions exploit architectural features that are unique to a computer.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] General-purpose instructions control architectural features common to all computers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] These are called *overlapping instructions*, *overlapping opcodes*, *overlapping code*, *overlapped code*, *instruction scission*, or *jump into the middle of an instruction*.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] In the 1970s and 1980s, overlapping instructions were sometimes used to preserve memory space.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] One example was in the implementation of error tables in Microsoft's Altair BASIC, where *interleaved instructions* mutually shared their instruction bytes.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The technique is rarely used today, but might still be necessary to resort to in areas where extreme optimization for size is necessary on the byte level such as in the implementation of boot loaders which have to fit into boot sectors.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] It is also sometimes used as a code obfuscation technique as a measure against disassembly and tampering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The principle is also used in shared code sequences of fat binaries which must run on multiple instruction-set-incompatible processor platforms.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] This property is also used to find unintended instructions called gadgets in existing code repositories and is used in return-oriented programming as alternative to code injection for exploits such as return-to-libc attacks.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] In some computers, the machine code of the architecture is implemented by an even more fundamental underlying layer called microcode, providing a common machine language interface across a line or family of different models of computer with widely different underlying dataflows.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] This is done to facilitate porting of machine language programs between different models.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] An example of this use is the IBM System/360 family of computers and their successors.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The IBM 650, introduced in 1954, was a decimal, word addressed computer with instructions and data stored on a magnetic drum.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Each word included ten digits plus sign.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Instructions divided the words into a two digit operation code, a four digit address of the data word to be processed and a four digit address of the next instruction to execute.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The second address allowed instructions to be placed on the drum near where the drum would be positioned after the previous instruction completed, a practice called optimization.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] With the aid of a physical table of op codes, it was quite feasible to write programs in machine code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] IBM provided a form with a grid showing each memory location, so a programmer could keep track of which locations were still available.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] There was a single-instruction-per-card format that could be loaded directly into the machine and executed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Later IBM introduced an assembler (SOAP) that allowed symbolic address and also performed a rough optimization pass.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The IBM 704, 709, 704x and 709x store one instruction in each instruction word; IBM numbers the bit from the left as S, 1, ..., 35.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] For all but the IBM 7094 and 7094 II, there are three index registers designated A, B and C; indexing with multiple 1 bits in the tag subtracts the logical or of the selected index registers and loading with multiple 1 bits in the tag loads all of the selected index registers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The effective address is normally Y-C(T), where C(T) is either 0 for a tag of 0, the logical or of the selected index registers in multiple tag mode or the selected index register if not in multiple tag mode.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] However, the effective address for index register control instructions is just Y.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] A flag with both bits 1 selects indirect addressing; the indirect address word has both a tag and a Y field.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] In addition to *transfer* (branch) instructions, these machines have skip instruction that conditionally skip one or two words, e.g., Compare Accumulator with Storage (CAS) does a three way compare and conditionally skips to NSI, NSI+1 or NSI+2, depending on the result.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The MIPS architecture provides a specific example for a machine code whose instructions are always 32 bits long.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] The general type of instruction is given by the *op* (operation) field, the highest 6 bits.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] J-type (jump) and I-type (immediate) instructions are fully specified by *op*.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] R-type (register) instructions include an additional *funct* (function) field to determine the exact operation.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Machine code is similar to yet fundamentally different from bytecode.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Like machine code, bytecode is typically generated (i.e. by a compiler) from source code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] But, unlike machine code, bytecode is not directly executable by a CPU.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] An exception is if a processor is designed to use bytecode as its machine code, such as the Pascal MicroEngine or a Java processor.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] If bytecode is processed by a software interpreter, then that interpreter is a virtual machine for which the bytecode is its machine code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] During execution, machine code is generally stored in RAM although running from ROM is supported by some devices.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Regardless, the code may also be cached in more specialized memory to enhance performance.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] There may be different caches for instructions and data, depending on the architecture.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] From the point of view of a process, the machine code lives in *code space*, a designated part of its address space.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] In a multi-threading environment, different threads of one process share code space along with data space, which reduces the overhead of context switching considerably as compared to process switching.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Machine code is generally considered to be not human readable, with Douglas Hofstadter comparing it to examining the atoms of a DNA molecule.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] However, various tools and methods support understanding machine code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] Disassembly decodes machine code to assembly language which is possible since assembly instructions can often be mapped one-to-one to machine instructions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] A decompiler converts machine code to a high-level language, but the result can be relatively obfuscated (hard to understand).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] A program can be associated with debug symbols (either embedded in the native executable or in a separate file) that allow it to be mapped to external source code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/machine-code] A debugger reads the symbols to help a programmer interactively debug the program.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The **National Security Agency** (**NSA**) is an intelligence agency of the United States Department of Defense, under the authority of the director of national intelligence (DNI).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is responsible for global monitoring, collection, and processing of information and data for intelligence and counterintelligence purposes, specializing in a discipline known as signals intelligence (SIGINT).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is also tasked with the protection of U.S. communications networks and information systems.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA relies on a variety of measures to accomplish its mission, the majority of which are clandestine.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Originating as a unit to decipher coded communications in World War II, it was officially formed as the NSA by President Harry S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Between then and the end of the Cold War, it became the largest of the U.S. intelligence organizations in terms of personnel and budget.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Still, information available as of 2013 indicates that the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) pulled ahead in this regard, with a budget of $14.7 billion.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA currently conducts worldwide mass data collection and has been known to physically bug electronic systems as one method to this end.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is also alleged to have been behind such attack software as Stuxnet, which severely damaged Iran's nuclear program.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA, alongside the CIA, maintains a physical presence in many countries across the globe; the CIA/NSA joint Special Collection Service (a highly classified intelligence team) inserts eavesdropping devices in high-value targets (such as presidential palaces or embassies).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] SCS collection tactics allegedly encompass "close surveillance, burglary, wiretapping, [and] breaking".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Unlike the CIA and the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA), both of which specialize primarily in foreign human espionage, the NSA does not publicly conduct human intelligence gathering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is entrusted with assisting with and coordinating SIGINT elements for other government organizations—which Executive Order prevents from engaging in such activities on their own.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] As part of these responsibilities, the agency has a co-located organization called the Central Security Service (CSS), which facilitates cooperation between the NSA and other U.S. defense cryptanalysis components.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] To further ensure streamlined communication between the signals intelligence community divisions, the NSA director simultaneously serves as the Commander of the United States Cyber Command and as Chief of the Central Security Service.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA's actions have been a matter of political controversy on several occasions, including its role in providing intelligence during the Gulf of Tonkin incident, which contributed to the escalation of U.S. involvement in the Vietnam War.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Declassified documents later revealed that the NSA misinterpreted or overstated signals intelligence, leading to reports of a second North Vietnamese attack that likely never occurred.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The agency has also received scrutiny for spying on anti–Vietnam War leaders and the agency's participation in economic espionage.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 2013, the NSA had many of its secret surveillance programs revealed to the public by Edward Snowden, a former NSA contractor.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] According to the leaked documents, the NSA intercepts and stores the communications of over a billion people worldwide, including United States citizens.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The documents also revealed that the NSA tracks hundreds of millions of people's movements using cell phone metadata.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Internationally, research has pointed to the NSA's ability to surveil the domestic Internet traffic of foreign countries through "boomerang routing".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The origins of the National Security Agency can be traced back to April 28, 1917, three weeks after the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Congress declared war on Germany in World War I.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] A code and cipher decryption unit was established as the Cable and Telegraph Section, which was also known as the Cipher Bureau.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It was headquartered in Washington, D.C., and was part of the war effort under the executive branch without direct congressional authorization.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] During the war, it was relocated in the army's organizational chart several times.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] At that point, the unit consisted of Yardley and two civilian clerks.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It absorbed the Navy's cryptanalysis functions in July 1918.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] World War I ended on November 11, 1918, and the army cryptographic section of Military Intelligence (MI-8) moved to New York City on May 20, 1919, where it continued intelligence activities as the Code Compilation Company under the direction of Yardley.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Army cryptographic section of military intelligence known as MI-8, the U.S. government created the Cipher Bureau, also known as Black Chamber, in 1919.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The Black Chamber was the United States' first peacetime cryptanalytic organization.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Jointly funded by the Army and the State Department, the Cipher Bureau was disguised as a New York City commercial code company; it produced and sold such codes for business use.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Its true mission, however, was to break the communications (chiefly diplomatic) of other nations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] At the Washington Naval Conference, it aided American negotiators by providing them with the decrypted traffic of many of the conference delegations, including the Japanese.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The Black Chamber successfully persuaded Western Union, the largest U.S. telegram company at the time, as well as several other communications companies, to illegally give the Black Chamber access to cable traffic of foreign embassies and consulates.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Soon, these companies publicly discontinued their collaboration.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Despite the Chamber's initial successes, it was shut down in 1929 by U.S. secretary of state Henry L.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] During World War II, the Signal Intelligence Service (SIS) was created to intercept and decipher the communications of the Axis powers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] When the war ended, the SIS was reorganized as the Army Security Agency (ASA), and it was placed under the leadership of the Director of Military Intelligence.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] On May 20, 1949, all cryptologic activities were centralized under a national organization called the Armed Forces Security Agency (AFSA).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] This organization was originally established within the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Department of Defense under the command of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The AFSA was tasked with directing the Department of Defense communications and electronic intelligence activities, except those of U.S. military intelligence units.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] However, the AFSA was unable to centralize communications intelligence and failed to coordinate with civilian agencies that shared its interests, such as the Department of State, the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Truman ordered a panel to investigate how AFSA had failed to achieve its goals.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The results of the investigation led to improvements and its redesignation as the National Security Agency.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The National Security Council issued a memorandum of October 24, 1952, that revised National Security Council Intelligence Directive (NSCID) 9.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] On the same day, Truman issued a second memorandum that called for the establishment of the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The actual establishment of the NSA was done by a November 4 memo by Robert A.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Lovett, the Secretary of Defense, changing the name of the AFSA to the NSA, and making the new agency responsible for all communications intelligence.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Since President Truman's memo was a classified document, the existence of the NSA was not known to the public at that time.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Due to its ultra-secrecy, the U.S. intelligence community referred to the NSA as "No Such Agency".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In the 1960s, the NSA played a key role in expanding American commitment to the Vietnam War by providing evidence of a North Vietnamese attack on the American Naval destroyer USS *Maddox* during the Gulf of Tonkin incident.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] However, the project turned out to be controversial, and an internal review by the NSA concluded that its Minaret program was "disreputable if not outright illegal".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA has mounted a major effort to secure tactical communications among U.S. armed forces during the war with mixed success.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NESTOR family of compatible secure voice systems it developed was widely deployed during the Vietnam War, with about 30,000 NESTOR sets produced.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] However, a variety of technical and operational problems limited their use, allowing the North Vietnamese to exploit and intercept U.S. communications.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA tracked these individuals in a secret filing system that was destroyed in 1974.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Following the resignation of President Richard Nixon, there were several investigations into suspected misuse of FBI, CIA and NSA facilities.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Senator Frank Church uncovered previously unknown activity, such as a CIA plot (ordered by the administration of President John F.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The investigation also uncovered NSA's wiretaps on targeted U.S. citizens.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] After the Church Committee hearings, the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act of 1978 was passed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] This was designed to limit the practice of mass surveillance in the United States.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 1986, the NSA intercepted the communications of the Libyan government during the immediate aftermath of the Berlin discotheque bombing.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The White House asserted that the NSA interception had provided "irrefutable" evidence that Libya was behind the bombing, which U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] President Ronald Reagan cited as a justification for the 1986 United States bombing of Libya.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 1999, a multi-year investigation by the European Parliament highlighted the NSA's role in economic espionage in a report entitled 'Development of Surveillance Technology and Risk of Abuse of Economic Information'.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] That year, the NSA founded the NSA Hall of Honor, a memorial at the National Cryptologic Museum in Fort Meade, Maryland.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The memorial is a, "tribute to the pioneers and heroes who have made significant and long-lasting contributions to American cryptology".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA employees must be retired for more than fifteen years to qualify for the memorial.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's infrastructure deteriorated in the 1990s as defense budget cuts resulted in maintenance deferrals.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] On January 24, 2000, NSA headquarters suffered a total network outage for three days caused by an overloaded network.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Incoming traffic was successfully stored on agency servers, but it could not be directed and processed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The agency carried out emergency repairs for $3 million to get the system running again (some incoming traffic was also directed instead to Britain's GCHQ for the time being).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Director Michael Hayden called the outage a "wake-up call" for the need to invest in the agency's infrastructure.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In the 1990s the defensive arm of the NSA—the Information Assurance Directorate (IAD)—started working more openly; the first public technical talk by an NSA scientist at a major cryptography conference was J.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Solinas' presentation on efficient Elliptic Curve Cryptography algorithms at Crypto 1997.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The IAD's cooperative approach to academia and industry culminated in its support for a transparent process for replacing the outdated Data Encryption Standard (DES) by an Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] After the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, the NSA believed that it had public support for a dramatic expansion of its surveillance activities.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In the aftermath of the September 11 attacks, the NSA created new IT systems to deal with the flood of information from new technologies like the Internet and cell phones.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] ThinThread contained advanced data mining capabilities.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It also had a "privacy mechanism"; surveillance was stored encrypted; decryption required a warrant.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The research done under this program may have contributed to the technology used in later systems.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] ThinThread was canceled when Michael Hayden chose Trailblazer, which did not include ThinThread's privacy system.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Trailblazer Project ramped up in 2002 and was worked on by Science Applications International Corporation (SAIC), Boeing, Computer Sciences Corporation, IBM, and Litton Industries.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Some NSA whistleblowers complained internally about major problems surrounding Trailblazer.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] This led to investigations by Congress and the NSA and DoD Inspectors General.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It was developed in small, inexpensive "test" pieces, rather than one grand plan like Trailblazer.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It also included offensive cyber-warfare capabilities, like injecting malware into remote computers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Congress criticized Turbulence in 2007 for having similar bureaucratic problems as Trailblazer.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It was to be a realization of information processing at higher speeds in cyberspace.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The massive extent of the NSA's spying, both foreign and domestic, was revealed to the public in a series of detailed disclosures of internal NSA documents beginning in June 2013.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Most of the disclosures were leaked by former NSA contractor Edward Snowden.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] On 4 September 2020, the NSA's surveillance program was ruled unlawful by the US Court of Appeals.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The court also added that the US intelligence leaders, who publicly defended it, were not telling the truth.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's eavesdropping mission includes radio broadcasting, both from various organizations and individuals, the Internet, telephone calls, and other intercepted forms of communication.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Its secure communications mission includes military, diplomatic, and all other sensitive, confidential, or secret government communications.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] According to a 2010 article in *The Washington Post*, "every day, collection systems at the National Security Agency intercept and store 1.7 billion e-mails, phone calls and other types of communications.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Because of its listening task, NSA/CSS has been heavily involved in cryptanalytic research, continuing the work of predecessor agencies which had broken many World War II codes and ciphers (see, for instance, Purple, Venona project, and JN-25).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 2004, NSA Central Security Service and the National Cyber Security Division of the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) agreed to expand the NSA Centers of Academic Excellence in Information Assurance Education Program.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] As part of the National Security Presidential Directive 54/Homeland Security Presidential Directive 23 (NSPD 54), signed on January 8, 2008, by President Bush, the NSA became the lead agency to monitor and protect all of the federal government's computer networks from cyber-terrorism.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] A part of the NSA's mission is to serve as a combat support agency for the Department of Defense.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] "Echelon" was created in the incubator of the Cold War.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Today it is a legacy system, and several NSA stations are closing.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Its capabilities were suspected to include the ability to monitor a large proportion of the world's transmitted civilian telephone, fax, and data traffic.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] During the early 1970s, the first of what became more than eight large satellite communications dishes were installed at Menwith Hill.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Investigative journalist Duncan Campbell reported in 1988 on the "ECHELON" surveillance program, an extension of the UKUSA Agreement on global signals intelligence SIGINT, and detailed how the eavesdropping operations worked.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] They confirmed that Menwith Hill was "linked directly to the headquarters of the US National Security Agency (NSA) at Fort Meade in Maryland".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's United States Signals Intelligence Directive 18 (USSID 18) strictly prohibited the interception or collection of information about "...
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] U.S. persons, entities, corporations or organizations...." without explicit written legal permission from the United States Attorney General when the subject is located abroad, or the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court when within U.S. borders.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Alleged Echelon-related activities, including its use for motives other than national security, including political and industrial espionage, received criticism from countries outside the UKUSA alliance.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA was also involved in planning to blackmail people with "SEXINT", intelligence gained about a potential target's sexual activity and preferences.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Those targeted had not committed any apparent crime nor were they charged with one.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] To support its facial recognition program, the NSA is intercepting "millions of images per day".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The Real Time Regional Gateway is a data collection program introduced in 2005 in Iraq by the NSA during the Iraq War that consisted of gathering all electronic communication, storing it, then searching and otherwise analyzing it.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It was effective in providing information about Iraqi insurgents who had eluded less comprehensive techniques.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] This "collect it all" strategy introduced by NSA director, Keith B.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Alexander, is believed by Glenn Greenwald of *The Guardian* to be the model for the comprehensive worldwide mass archiving of communications which NSA is engaged in as of 2013.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] A dedicated unit of the NSA locates targets for the CIA for extrajudicial assassination in the Middle East.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA has also spied extensively on the European Union, the United Nations, and numerous governments including allies and trading partners in Europe, South America, and Asia.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In June 2015, WikiLeaks published documents showing that NSA spied on French companies.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] WikiLeaks also published documents showing that NSA spied on federal German ministries since the 1990s.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Even Germany's Chancellor Angela Merkel's cellphones and phones of her predecessors had been intercepted.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In June 2013, Edward Snowden revealed that between 8 February and 8 March 2013, the NSA collected about 124.8 billion telephone data items and 97.1 billion computer data items throughout the world, as was displayed in charts from an internal NSA tool codenamed Boundless Informant.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Initially, it was reported that some of these data reflected eavesdropping on citizens in countries like Germany, Spain, and France, but later on, it became clear that those data were collected by European agencies during military missions abroad and were subsequently shared with NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] This memo appears to give credence to previous speculation by cryptographers at Microsoft Research.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Edward Snowden claims that the NSA often bypasses the encryption process altogether by lifting information before encryption or after decryption.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Linus Torvalds, the founder of Linux kernel, joked during a LinuxCon keynote on September 18, 2013, that the NSA, who is the founder of SELinux, wanted a backdoor in the kernel.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] However, later, Linus' father, a Member of the European Parliament (MEP), revealed that the NSA actually did this.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] IBM Notes was the first widely adopted software product to use public key cryptography for client-server and server–server authentication and encryption of data.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Until US laws regulating encryption were changed in 2000, IBM and Lotus were prohibited from exporting versions of Notes that supported symmetric encryption keys that were longer than 40 bits.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 1997, Lotus negotiated an agreement with the NSA that allowed the export of a version that supported stronger keys with 64 bits, but 24 of the bits were encrypted with a special key and included in the message to provide a "workload reduction factor" for the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] This strengthened the protection for users of Notes outside the US against private-sector industrial espionage, but not against spying by the US government.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] While it is assumed that foreign transmissions terminating in the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] (such as a non-U.S. citizen accessing a U.S. website) subject non-U.S. citizens to NSA surveillance, recent research into boomerang routing has raised new concerns about the NSA's ability to surveil the domestic Internet traffic of foreign countries.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Boomerang routing occurs when an Internet transmission that originates and terminates in a single country transits another.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Research at the University of Toronto has suggested that approximately 25% of Canadian domestic traffic may be subject to NSA surveillance activities as a result of the boomerang routing of Canadian Internet service providers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Intercepted packages are opened carefully by NSA employees.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] A document included in the NSA files released with Glenn Greenwald's book *No Place to Hide* details how the agency's Tailored Access Operations (TAO) and other NSA units gained access to hardware equipment.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] They intercepted routers, servers, and other network hardware equipment being shipped to organizations targeted for surveillance and installing covert implant firmware onto them before they are delivered.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Computers that were seized by the NSA due to interdiction are often modified with a physical device known as Cottonmouth.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It is a device that can be inserted at the USB port of a computer to establish remote access to the targeted machine.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's mission, as outlined in Executive Order 12333 in 1981, is to collect information that constitutes "foreign intelligence or counterintelligence" while *not* "acquiring information concerning the domestic activities of United States persons".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA has declared that it relies on the FBI to collect information on foreign intelligence activities within the borders of the United States while confining its activities within the United States to the embassies and missions of foreign nations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The appearance of a 'Domestic Surveillance Directorate' of the NSA was soon exposed as a hoax in 2013.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's domestic surveillance activities are limited by the requirements imposed by the Fourth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The specific requirements for domestic surveillance operations are contained in the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act of 1978 (FISA), which does not extend protection to non-U.S. citizens located outside of U.S. territory.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Bush, president during the 9/11 terrorist attacks, approved the Patriot Act shortly after the attacks to take anti-terrorist security measures.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Titles 1, 2, and 9 specifically authorized measures that would be taken by the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] These titles granted enhanced domestic security against terrorism, surveillance procedures, and improved intelligence, respectively.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] On March 10, 2004, there was a debate between President Bush and White House Counsel Alberto Gonzales, Attorney General John Ashcroft, and Acting Attorney General James Comey.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The Attorneys General were unsure if the NSA's programs could be considered constitutional.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] They threatened to resign over the matter, but ultimately the NSA's programs continued.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] On March 11, 2004, President Bush signed a new authorization for mass surveillance of Internet records, in addition to the surveillance of phone records.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] This allowed the president to be able to override laws such as the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act, which protected civilians from mass surveillance.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In addition to this, President Bush also signed that the measures of mass surveillance were also retroactively in place.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] One such surveillance program, authorized by the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Signals Intelligence Directive 18 of President George Bush, was the Highlander Project undertaken for the National Security Agency by the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Army 513th Military Intelligence Brigade.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA relayed telephone (including cell phone) conversations obtained from ground, airborne, and satellite monitoring stations to various U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Army Signal Intelligence Officers, including the 201st Military Intelligence Battalion.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Conversations of citizens of the U.S. were intercepted, along with those of other nations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Proponents of the surveillance program claim that the President has executive authority to order such action, arguing that laws such as FISA are overridden by the President's Constitutional powers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In addition, some argued that FISA was implicitly overridden by a subsequent statute, the Authorization for Use of Military Force, although the Supreme Court's ruling in *Hamdan v.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Under the PRISM program, which started in 2007, NSA gathers Internet communications from foreign targets from nine major U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Internet-based communication service providers: Microsoft, Yahoo, Google, Facebook, PalTalk, AOL, Skype, YouTube and Apple.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Data gathered include email, videos, photos, VoIP chats such as Skype, and file transfers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Former NSA director General Keith Alexander claimed that in September 2009 the NSA prevented Najibullah Zazi and his friends from carrying out a terrorist attack.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] However, no evidence has been presented demonstrating that the NSA has ever been instrumental in preventing a terrorist attack.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The FASCIA database stores various types of information, including Location Area Codes (LACs), Cell Tower IDs (CeLLIDs), Visitor Location Registers (VLRs), International Mobile Station Equipment Identity (IMEIs) and MSISDNs (Mobile Subscriber Integrated Services Digital Network-Numbers).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Over about seven months, more than 27 terabytes of location data were collected and stored in the database.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Commercial Solutions for Classified (CSfC) is a key component of the NSA's commercial cybersecurity strategy.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] CSfC-validated commercial products are proven to meet rigorous security requirements for protection of classified National Security Systems (NSS) data.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Once validated, the Department of Defense (DoD), Intelligence Community, Military Services, and other U.S. government agencies are able to implement these commercial hardware and software technologies into their data protection and cybersecurity solutions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Besides the more traditional ways of eavesdropping to collect signals intelligence, the NSA is also engaged in hacking computers, smartphones, and their networks.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] A division that conducts such operations is the Tailored Access Operations (TAO) division, which has been active since at least circa 1998.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is led by the Director of the National Security Agency (DIRNSA), who also serves as Chief of the Central Security Service (CHCSS) and Commander of the United States Cyber Command (USCYBERCOM) and is the highest-ranking military official of these organizations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] He is assisted by a Deputy Director, who is the highest-ranking civilian within the NSA/CSS.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA also has an Inspector General, head of the Office of the Inspector General (OIG); a General Counsel, head of the Office of the General Counsel (OGC); and a Director of Compliance, who is head of the Office of the Director of Compliance (ODOC).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The National Security Agency Office of Inspector General has worked on cases in collaboration with the United States Department of Justice and the Central Intelligence Agency Office of Inspector General.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Unlike other intelligence organizations such as the CIA or DIA, the NSA has always been particularly reticent concerning its internal organizational structure.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Each of these directorates consisted of several groups or elements, designated by a letter.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] There were for example the A Group, which was responsible for all SIGINT operations against the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe, and the G Group, which was responsible for SIGINT related to all non-communist countries.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] These groups were divided into units designated by an additional number, like unit A5 for breaking Soviet codes, and G6, being the office for the Middle East, North Africa, Cuba, and Central and South America.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] As of 2013, NSA has about a dozen directorates, which are designated by a letter, although not all of them are publicly known.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In the year 2000, a leadership team was formed consisting of the director, the deputy director, and the directors of the Signals Intelligence (SID), the Information Assurance (IAD) and the Technical Directorate (TD).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The chiefs of other main NSA divisions became associate directors of the senior leadership team.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Bush initiated the President's Surveillance Program (PSP) in 2001, the NSA created a 24-hour Metadata Analysis Center (MAC), followed in 2004 by the Advanced Analysis Division (AAD), with the mission of analyzing content, Internet metadata and telephone metadata.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Both units were part of the Signals Intelligence Directorate.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 2016, a proposal combined the Signals Intelligence Directorate with the Information Assurance Directorate into a Directorate of Operations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSANet stands for National Security Agency Network and is the official NSA intranet.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It is a classified network, for information up to the level of TS/SCI to support the use and sharing of intelligence data between NSA and the signals intelligence agencies of the four other nations of the Five Eyes partnership.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The management of NSANet has been delegated to the Central Security Service Texas (CSSTEXAS).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSANet is a highly secured computer network consisting of fiber-optic and satellite communication channels that are almost completely separated from the public Internet.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The network allows NSA personnel and civilian and military intelligence analysts anywhere in the world to have access to the agency's systems and databases.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] This access is tightly controlled and monitored.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] For example, every keystroke is logged, activities are audited at random, and downloading and printing of documents from NSANet are recorded.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 1998, NSANet, along with NIPRNet and SIPRNet, had "significant problems with poor search capabilities, unorganized data, and old information".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 2004, the network was reported to have used over twenty commercial off-the-shelf operating systems.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Some universities that do highly sensitive research are allowed to connect to it.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The thousands of Top Secret internal NSA documents that were taken by Edward Snowden in 2013 were stored in "a file-sharing location on the NSA's intranet site"; so, they could easily be read online by NSA personnel.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Everyone with a TS/SCI clearance had access to these documents.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] As a system administrator, Snowden was responsible for moving accidentally misplaced highly sensitive documents to safer storage locations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA has its law enforcement team, known as the *NSA Police* (and formerly as *NSA Security Protective Force*) which provides law enforcement services, emergency response, and physical security to its officials and properties.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA Police has a K9 division, which generally conducts explosive detection screening of mail, vehicles, and cargo entering NSA grounds.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] They use marked vehicles to carry out patrols.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The number of NSA employees is officially classified but there are several sources providing estimates.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 1961, the NSA had 59,000 military and civilian employees, which grew to 93,067 in 1969, of which 19,300 worked at the headquarters at Fort Meade.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In the early 1980s, NSA had roughly 50,000 military and civilian personnel.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] By 1989 this number had grown again to 75,000, of which 25,000 worked at the NSA headquarters.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Between 1990 and 1995 the NSA's budget and workforce were cut by one-third, which led to a substantial loss of experience.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 2012, the NSA said more than 30,000 employees worked at Fort Meade and other facilities.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Inglis, the deputy director, said that the total number of NSA employees is "somewhere between 37,000 and one billion" as a joke, and stated that the agency is "probably the biggest employer of introverts." In 2013 *Der Spiegel* stated that the NSA had 40,000 employees.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] More widely, it has been described as the world's largest single employer of mathematicians.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Some NSA employees form part of the workforce of the National Reconnaissance Office (NRO), the agency that provides the NSA with satellite signals intelligence.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] As of 2013 about 1,000 system administrators work for the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA received criticism early on in 1960 after two agents had defected to the Soviet Union.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Nonetheless, security breaches reoccurred only a year later when in an issue of *Izvestia* of July 23, 1963, a former NSA employee published several cryptologic secrets.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The very same day, an NSA clerk-messenger committed suicide as ongoing investigations disclosed that he had sold secret information to the Soviets regularly.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Edward Snowden's leaking of the existence of PRISM in 2013 caused the NSA to institute a "two-man rule", where two system administrators are required to be present when one accesses certain sensitive information.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Snowden claims he suggested such a rule in 2009.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA conducts polygraph tests of employees.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] For new employees, the tests are meant to discover enemy spies who are applying to the NSA and to uncover any information that could make an applicant pliant to coercion.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] As part of the latter, historically *EPQs* or "embarrassing personal questions" about sexual behavior had been included in the NSA polygraph.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA also conducts five-year periodic reinvestigation polygraphs of employees, focusing on counterintelligence programs.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In addition, the NSA conducts periodic polygraph investigations to find spies and leakers; those who refuse to take them may receive "termination of employment", according to a 1982 memorandum from the director of the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] There are also "special access examination" polygraphs for employees who wish to work in highly sensitive areas, and those polygraphs cover counterintelligence questions and some questions about behavior.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's brochure states that the average test length is between two and four hours.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] Between 1974 and 1979, of the 20,511 job applicants who took polygraph tests, 695 (3.4%) confessed to previous felony crimes; almost all of those crimes had been undetected.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 2010 the NSA produced a video explaining its polygraph process.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The video, ten minutes long, is titled "The Truth About the Polygraph" and was posted to the Web site of the Defense Security Service.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] George Maschke, the founder of the Web site, accused the NSA polygraph video of being "Orwellian".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] In 2013, an article indicated that after Edward Snowden revealed his identity in 2013, the NSA began requiring polygraphing of employees once per quarter.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] The number of exemptions from legal requirements has been criticized.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] When in 1964 Congress was hearing a bill giving the director of the NSA the power to fire at will any employee, *The Washington Post* wrote: "This is the very definition of arbitrariness.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p01] It means that an employee could be discharged and disgraced based on anonymous allegations without the slightest opportunity to defend himself." Yet, the bill was accepted by an overwhelming majority.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] When the agency was first established, its headquarters and cryptographic center were in the Naval Security Station in Washington, D.C.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The COMINT functions were located in Arlington Hall in Northern Virginia, which served as the headquarters of the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Because the Soviet Union had detonated a nuclear bomb and because the facilities were crowded, the federal government wanted to move several agencies, including the AFSA/NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] A planning committee considered Fort Knox, but Fort Meade, Maryland, was ultimately chosen as NSA headquarters because it was far enough away from Washington, D.C. in case of a nuclear strike and was close enough so its employees would not have to move their families.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Construction of additional buildings began after the agency occupied buildings at Fort Meade in the late 1950s, which they soon outgrew.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 1963 the new headquarters building, nine stories tall, opened.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA workers referred to the building as the "Headquarters Building" and since the NSA management occupied the top floor, workers used "Ninth Floor" to refer to their leaders.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] COMSEC remained in Washington, D.C., until its new building was completed in 1968.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In September 1986, the Operations 2A and 2B buildings, both copper-shielded to prevent eavesdropping, opened with a dedication by President Ronald Reagan.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The four NSA buildings became known as the "Big Four." The NSA director moved to 2B when it opened.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Meade, Maryland, although it is separate from other compounds and agencies that are based within this same military installation.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Fort Meade is about 20 mi (32 km) southwest of Baltimore, and 25 mi (40 km) northeast of Washington, D.C.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA has two dedicated exits off Baltimore–Washington Parkway.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The Eastbound exit from the Parkway (heading toward Baltimore) is open to the public and provides employee access to its main campus and public access to the National Cryptology Museum.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The Westbound side exit, (heading toward Washington) is labeled "NSA Employees Only".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The exit may only be used by people with the proper clearances, and security vehicles parked along the road guard the entrance.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA is the largest employer in the state of Maryland, and two-thirds of its personnel work at Fort Meade.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Built on 350 acres (140 ha; 0.55 sq mi) of Fort Meade's 5,000 acres (2,000 ha; 7.8 sq mi), the site has 1,300 buildings and an estimated 18,000 parking spaces.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It contains 3,000,000 square feet (280,000 m2), or more than 68 acres (28 ha), of floor space; Bamford said that the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The facility has over 100 watchposts, one of them being the visitor control center, a two-story area that serves as the entrance.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] At the entrance, a white pentagonal structure, visitor badges are issued to visitors and security clearances of employees are checked.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The visitor center includes a painting of the NSA seal.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The OPS2A building, the tallest building in the NSA complex and the location of much of the agency's operations directorate is accessible from the visitor center.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Bamford described it as a "dark glass Rubik's Cube".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The facility's "red corridor" houses non-security operations such as concessions and the drug store.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The name refers to the "red badge" which is worn by someone without a security clearance.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA headquarters includes a cafeteria, a credit union, ticket counters for airlines and entertainment, a barbershop, and a bank.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA headquarters has its own post office, fire department, and police force.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The employees at the NSA headquarters reside in various places in the Baltimore-Washington area, including Annapolis, Baltimore, and Columbia in Maryland and the District of Columbia, including the Georgetown community.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA maintains a shuttle service from the Odenton station of MARC to its Visitor Control Center and has done so since 2005.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Following a major power outage in 2000, in 2003, and follow-ups through 2007, *The Baltimore Sun* reported that the NSA was at risk of electrical overload because of insufficient internal electrical infrastructure at Fort Meade to support the amount of equipment being installed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] On August 6, 2006, *The Baltimore Sun* reported that the NSA had completely maxed out the grid and that Baltimore Gas & Electric (BGE, now Constellation Energy) was unable to sell them any more power.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA decided to move some of its operations to a new satellite facility.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] BGE provided NSA with 65 to 75 megawatts at Fort Meade in 2007 and expected that an increase of 10 to 15 megawatts would be needed later that year.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 2011, the NSA was Maryland's largest consumer of power.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 2007, as BGE's largest customer, NSA bought as much electricity as Annapolis, the capital city of Maryland.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] One estimate put the potential for power consumption by the new Utah Data Center at US$40 million per year.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 1995, *The Baltimore Sun* reported that the NSA is the owner of the single largest group of supercomputers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA held a groundbreaking ceremony at Fort Meade in May 2013 for its High-Performance Computing Center 2, expected to open in 2016.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Called Site M, the center has a 150-megawatt power substation, 14 administrative buildings and 10 parking garages.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The center is 1,800,000 square feet (17 ha; 0.065 sq mi) and initially uses 60 megawatts of electricity.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Increments II and III are expected to be completed by 2030 and would quadruple the space, covering 5,800,000 square feet (54 ha; 0.21 sq mi) with 60 buildings and 40 parking garages.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Defense contractors are also establishing or expanding cybersecurity facilities near the NSA and around the Washington metropolitan area.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The DoD Computer Security Center was founded in 1981 and renamed the National Computer Security Center (NCSC) in 1985.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NCSC was responsible for computer security throughout the federal government.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NCSC was part of NSA, and during the late 1980s and the 1990s, NSA and NCSC published Trusted Computer System Evaluation Criteria in a six-foot high Rainbow Series of books that detailed trusted computing and network platform specifications.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The Rainbow books were replaced by the Common Criteria, however, in the early 2000s.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 2009, to protect its assets and access more electricity, NSA sought to decentralize and expand its existing facilities in Fort Meade and Menwith Hill, the latter expansion expected to be completed by 2015.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] On January 6, 2011, a groundbreaking ceremony was held to begin construction on the NSA's first Comprehensive National Cyber-security Initiative (CNCI) Data Center, known as the "Utah Data Center" for short.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The $1.5B data center is being built at Camp Williams, Utah, located 25 miles (40 km) south of Salt Lake City, and will help support the agency's National Cyber-security Initiative.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It is expected to be operational by September 2013.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Construction of Utah Data Center finished in May 2019.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 2012, NSA collected intelligence from four geostationary satellites.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Satellite receivers were at Roaring Creek Station in Catawissa, Pennsylvania and Salt Creek Station in Arbuckle, California.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It operated ten to twenty taps on U.S. telecom switches.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA had installations in several U.S. states and from them observed intercepts from Europe, the Middle East, North Africa, Latin America, and Asia.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The *Yakima Herald-Republic* cited Bamford, saying that many of NSA's bases for its Echelon program were a legacy system, using outdated, 1990s technology.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 2004, NSA closed its operations at Bad Aibling Station (Field Station 81) in Bad Aibling, Germany.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 2012, NSA began to move some of its operations at Yakima Research Station, Yakima Training Center, in Washington state to Colorado, planning to leave Yakima closed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] During 2013, NSA also intended to close operations at Sugar Grove, West Virginia.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA operates RAF Menwith Hill in North Yorkshire, United Kingdom, which was, according to BBC News in 2007, the largest electronic monitoring station in the world.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The agency's European Cryptologic Center (ECC), with 240 employees in 2011, is headquartered at a US military compound in Griesheim, near Frankfurt in Germany.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] A 2011 NSA report indicates that the ECC is responsible for the "largest analysis and productivity in Europe" and focuses on various priorities, including Africa, Europe, the Middle East, and counterterrorism operations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Since the mid-1980s, the NSA and Taiwan's National Security Bureau have jointly operated a signals intelligence (SIGINT) listening station at Yangmingshan.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 2013, a new Consolidated Intelligence Center, also to be used by NSA, is being built at the headquarters of the United States Army Europe in Wiesbaden, Germany.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA's partnership with Bundesnachrichtendienst (BND), the German foreign intelligence service, was confirmed by BND president Gerhard Schindler.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Thailand is a "3rd party partner" of the NSA along with nine other nations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] These are non-English-speaking countries that have made security agreements for the exchange of SIGINT raw material and end product reports.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Thailand is the site of at least two US SIGINT collection stations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] One is at the US Embassy in Bangkok, an NSA-CIA Joint Special Collection Service (JSCS) unit.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It presumably eavesdrops on foreign consulates, embassies, governmental communications, and other targets of opportunity.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The second installation is a FORNSAT (foreign satellite interception) station in the Thai city of Khon Kaen.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It is codenamed INDRA, but has also been referred to as LEMONWOOD.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The station is approximately 40 hectares (99 acres) in size and consists of a large 3,700–4,600 m2 (40,000–50,000 ft2) operations building on the west side of the ops compound and four radome-enclosed parabolic antennas.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Possibly two of the radome-enclosed antennas are used for SATCOM intercept and two antennas are used for relaying the intercepted material back to the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] There is also a PUSHER-type circularly-disposed antenna array (CDAA) just north of the ops compound.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA activated Khon Kaen in October 1979.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Its mission was to eavesdrop on the radio traffic of Chinese army and air force units in southern China, especially in and around the city of Kunming in Yunnan Province.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The base fell into disrepair in the 1990s as China and Vietnam became more friendly towards the US, and by 2002 archived satellite imagery showed that the PUSHER CDAA antenna had been torn down, perhaps indicating that the base had been closed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] At some point in the period since 9/11, the Khon Kaen base was reactivated and expanded to include a sizeable SATCOM intercept mission.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It is likely that the NSA presence at Khon Kaen is relatively small, and that most of the work is done by civilian contractors.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA has been involved in debates about public policy, both indirectly as a behind-the-scenes adviser to other departments, and directly during and after Vice Admiral Bobby Ray Inman's directorship.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA was a major player in the debates of the 1990s regarding the export of cryptography in the United States.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Restrictions on export were reduced but not eliminated in 1996.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Its secure government communications work has involved the NSA in numerous technology areas, including the design of specialized communications hardware and software, production of dedicated semiconductors at the Ft.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Meade chip fabrication plant), and advanced cryptography research.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] For 50 years, the NSA designed and built most of its in-house computer equipment, but from the 1990s until about 2003 (when the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Congress curtailed the practice), the agency contracted with the private sector in the fields of research and equipment.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA was embroiled in some controversy concerning its involvement in the creation of the Data Encryption Standard (DES), a standard and public block cipher algorithm used by the U.S. government and banking community.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] During the development of DES by IBM in the 1970s, NSA recommended changes to some details of the design.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It has since been observed that the S-boxes in DES are particularly resilient against differential cryptanalysis, a technique that was not publicly discovered until the late 1980s but known to the IBM DES team.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The involvement of the NSA in selecting a successor to the Data Encryption Standard (DES), the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES), was limited to hardware performance testing.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA has subsequently certified AES for protection of classified information when used in NSA-approved systems.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The widely used SHA-1 and SHA-2 hash functions were designed by NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] SHA-1 is a slight modification of the weaker SHA-0 algorithm, also designed by NSA in 1993.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] This small modification was suggested by the NSA two years later, with no justification other than the fact that it provides additional security.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] An attack for SHA-0 that does not apply to the revised algorithm was indeed found between 1998 and 2005 by academic cryptographers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Because of weaknesses and key length restrictions in SHA-1, NIST deprecates its use for digital signatures and approves only the newer SHA-2 algorithms for such applications from 2013 on.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] A new hash standard, SHA-3, has recently been selected through the competition concluded on October 2, 2012, with the selection of Keccak as the algorithm.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The process to select SHA-3 was similar to the one held in choosing the AES, but some doubts have been cast over it, since fundamental modifications have been made to Keccak to turn it into a standard.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] These changes potentially undermine the cryptanalysis performed during the competition and reduce the security levels of the algorithm.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The proposal was strongly opposed and key escrow requirements ultimately went nowhere.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] However, NSA's Fortezza hardware-based encryption cards, created for the Clipper project, are still used within government, and NSA ultimately declassified and published the design of the Skipjack cipher used on the cards.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA promoted the inclusion of a random number generator called Dual EC DRBG in the U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] National Institute of Standards and Technology's 2007 guidelines.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] This led to speculation of a backdoor which would allow NSA access to data encrypted by systems using that pseudorandom number generator (PRNG).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] This is now deemed to be plausible based on the fact that output of next iterations of PRNG can provably be determined if relation between two internal Elliptic Curve points is known.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Both NIST and RSA are now officially recommending against the use of this PRNG.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Perfect Citizen is a program to perform vulnerability assessment by the NSA in the American critical infrastructure.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It was originally reported to be a program to develop a system of sensors to detect cyber attacks on critical infrastructure computer networks in both the private and public sector through a network monitoring system named *Einstein*.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It is funded by the Comprehensive National Cybersecurity Initiative and thus far Raytheon has received a contract for up to $100 million for the initial stage.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA has invested many millions of dollars in academic research under grant code prefix *MDA904*, resulting in over 3,000 papers as of October 11, 2007.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA publishes its documents through various publications.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Despite this, the NSA/CSS has, at times, attempted to restrict the publication of academic research into cryptography; for example, the Khufu and Khafre block ciphers were voluntarily withheld in response to an NSA request to do so.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In response to a FOIA lawsuit, in 2013 the NSA released the 643-page research paper titled, "Untangling the Web: A Guide to Internet Research", written and compiled by NSA employees to assist other NSA workers in searching for information of interest to the agency on the public Internet.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Patent and Trademark Office under gag order.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Unlike normal patents, these are not revealed to the public and do not expire.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] However, if the Patent Office receives an application for an identical patent from a third party, they will reveal the NSA's patent and officially grant it to the NSA for the full term on that date.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] One of NSA's published patents describes a method of geographically locating an individual computer site in an Internet-like network, based on the latency of multiple network connections.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Although no public patent exists, NSA is reported to have used a similar locating technology called trilateralization that allows real-time tracking of an individual's location, including altitude from ground level, using data obtained from cellphone towers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The heraldic insignia of NSA consists of an eagle inside a circle, grasping a key in its talons.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The eagle represents the agency's national mission.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Its breast features a shield with bands of red and white, taken from the Great Seal of the United States and representing Congress.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The key is taken from the emblem of Saint Peter and represents security.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] When the NSA was created, the agency had no emblem and used that of the Department of Defense.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The agency adopted its first of two emblems in 1963.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The current NSA insignia has been in use since 1965, when then-Director, LTG Marshall S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Carter (USA) ordered the creation of a device to represent the agency.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA's flag consists of the agency's seal on a light blue background.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Crews associated with NSA missions have been involved in several dangerous and deadly situations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The USS *Liberty* incident in 1967 and USS *Pueblo* incident in 1968 are examples of the losses endured during the Cold War.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The National Security Agency/Central Security Service Cryptologic Memorial honors and remembers the fallen personnel, both military and civilian, of these intelligence missions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It is made of black granite, and has 171 names carved into it, as of 2013.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] A tradition of declassifying the stories of the fallen was begun in 2001.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In the United States, at least since 2001, there has been legal controversy over what signal intelligence can be used for and how much freedom the National Security Agency has to use signal intelligence.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In 2015, the government made slight changes in how it uses and collects certain types of data, specifically phone records.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The government was not analyzing the phone records as of early 2019.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The surveillance programs were deemed unlawful in September 2020 in a court of appeals case.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] On December 16, 2005, *The New York Times* reported that under White House pressure and with an executive order from President George W.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Edward Snowden is a former American intelligence contractor who revealed in 2013 the existence of secret wide-ranging information-gathering programs conducted by the National Security Agency (NSA).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] More specifically, Snowden released information that demonstrated how the United States government was gathering immense amounts of personal communications, emails, phone locations, web histories and more of American citizens without their knowledge.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] One of Snowden's primary motivators for releasing this information was fear of a surveillance state developing as a result of the infrastructure being created by the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] As Snowden recounts, "I believe that, at this point in history, the greatest danger to our freedom and way of life comes from the reasonable fear of omniscient State powers kept in check by nothing more than policy documents...
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It is not that I do not value intelligence, but that I oppose . . . omniscient, automatic, mass surveillance. . . .
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] On January 17, 2006, the Center for Constitutional Rights filed a lawsuit, CCR v.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The lawsuit challenged the National Security Agency's (NSA's) surveillance of people within the U.S., including the interception of CCR emails without securing a warrant first.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] District Court Judge Anna Diggs Taylor concluded that NSA's warrantless surveillance program was both illegal and unconstitutional.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] On July 6, 2007, the 6th Circuit Court of Appeals vacated the decision because the ACLU lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] As a result of the USA Freedom Act passed by Congress in June 2015, the NSA had to shut down its bulk phone surveillance program on November 29 of the same year.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The USA Freedom Act forbids the NSA to collect metadata and content of phone calls unless it has a warrant for terrorism investigation.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In that case, the agency must ask the telecom companies for the record, which will only be kept for six months.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA's use of large telecom companies to assist it with its surveillance efforts has caused several privacy concerns.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In May 2008, Mark Klein, a former AT&T employee, alleged that his company had cooperated with NSA in installing Narus hardware to replace the FBI Carnivore program, to monitor network communications including traffic between U.S. citizens.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA was reported in 2008 to use its computing capability to analyze "transactional" data that it regularly acquires from other government agencies, which gather it under their jurisdictional authorities.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] A 2013 advisory group for the Obama administration, seeking to reform NSA spying programs following the revelations of documents released by Edward J.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Clarke was a group member and stated on April 11, 2014, that NSA had no advance knowledge of Heartbleed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Law enforcement agents were directed to conceal how the investigations began and recreate a legal investigative trail by re-obtaining the same evidence by other means.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In the months leading to April 2009, the NSA intercepted the communications of U.S. citizens, including a congressman, although the Justice Department believed that the interception was unintentional.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The Justice Department then took action to correct the issues and bring the program into compliance with existing laws.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] United States Attorney General Eric Holder resumed the program according to his understanding of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act amendment of 2008, without explaining what had occurred.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Polls conducted in June 2013 found divided results among Americans regarding NSA's secret data collection.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Rasmussen Reports found that 59% of Americans disapprove, Gallup found that 53% disapprove, and Pew found that 56% are in favor of NSA data collection.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] On April 25, 2013, the NSA obtained a court order requiring Verizon's Business Network Services to provide metadata on all calls in its system to the NSA "on an ongoing daily basis" for three months, as reported by *The Guardian* on June 6, 2013.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] This information includes "the numbers of both parties on a call ... location data, call duration, unique identifiers, and the time and duration of all calls" but not "[t]he contents of the conversation itself".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The order relies on the so-called "business records" provision of the Patriot Act.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In August 2013, following the Snowden leaks, new details about the NSA's data mining activity were revealed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Reportedly, the majority of emails into or out of the United States are captured at "selected communications links" and automatically analyzed for keywords or other "selectors".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The utility of such a massive metadata collection in preventing terrorist attacks is disputed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Many studies reveal the dragnet-like system to be ineffective.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Defenders of the program said that while metadata alone cannot provide all the information necessary to prevent an attack, it assures the ability to "connect the dots" between suspect foreign numbers and domestic numbers with a speed only the NSA's software is capable of.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] One benefit of this is quickly being able to determine the difference between suspicious activity and real threats.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] As an example, NSA director General Keith B.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Alexander mentioned at the annual Cybersecurity Summit in 2013, that metadata analysis of domestic phone call records after the Boston Marathon bombing helped determine that rumors of a follow-up attack in New York were baseless.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In addition to doubts about its effectiveness, many people argue that the collection of metadata is an unconstitutional invasion of privacy.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] As of 2015, the collection process remained legal and grounded in the ruling from *Smith v.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] A prominent opponent of the data collection and its legality is U.S.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] As of May 7, 2015, the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit ruled that the interpretation of Section 215 of the Patriot Act was wrong and that the NSA program that has been collecting Americans' phone records in bulk is illegal.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It stated that Section 215 cannot be interpreted to allow government to collect national phone data and, as a result, expired on June 1, 2015.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Under the Upstream collection program, the NSA paid telecommunications companies hundreds of millions of dollars in order to collect data from them.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] While companies such as Google and Yahoo! claim that they do not provide "direct access" from their servers to the NSA unless under a court order, the NSA had access to emails, phone calls, and cellular data users.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Under this new ruling, telecommunications companies maintain bulk user metadata on their servers for at least 18 months, to be provided upon request to the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] This ruling made the mass storage of specific phone records at NSA datacenters illegal, but it did not rule on Section 215's constitutionality.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In a declassified document it was revealed that 17,835 phone lines were on an improperly permitted "alert list" from 2006 to 2009 in breach of compliance, which tagged these phone lines for daily monitoring.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Eleven percent of these monitored phone lines met the agency's legal standard for "reasonably articulable suspicion" (RAS).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA tracks the locations of hundreds of millions of cell phones per day, allowing it to map people's movements and relationships in detail.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA has been reported to have access to all communications made via Google, Microsoft, Facebook, Yahoo, YouTube, AOL, Skype, Apple and Paltalk, and collects hundreds of millions of contact lists from personal email and instant messaging accounts each year.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It has also managed to weaken much of the encryption used on the Internet (by collaborating with, coercing, or otherwise infiltrating numerous technology companies to leave "backdoors" into their systems) so that the majority of encryption is inadvertently vulnerable to different forms of attack.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Domestically, the NSA has been proven to collect and store metadata records of phone calls, including over 120 million US Verizon subscribers, as well as intercept vast amounts of communications via the internet (Upstream).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The government's legal standing had been to rely on a secret interpretation of the Patriot Act whereby the entirety of US communications may be considered "relevant" to a terrorism investigation if it is expected that even a tiny minority may relate to terrorism.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA also supplies foreign intercepts to the DEA, IRS and other law enforcement agencies, who use these to initiate criminal investigations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Federal agents are then instructed to "recreate" the investigative trail via parallel construction.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA also spies on influential Muslim societies to obtain information that could be used to discredit them, such as their use of pornography.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The targets, both domestic and abroad, are not suspected of any crime but hold religious or political views deemed "radical" by the NSA.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] According to a report in *The Washington Post* in July 2014, relying on information provided by Snowden, 90% of those placed under surveillance in the U.S. are ordinary Americans and are not the intended targets.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The newspaper said it had examined documents including emails, text messages, and online accounts that support the claim.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The Intelligence Committees of the US House and Senate exercise primary oversight over the NSA; other members of Congress have been denied access to materials and information regarding the agency and its activities.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The United States Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court, the secret court charged with regulating the NSA's activities is, according to its chief judge, incapable of investigating or verifying how often the NSA breaks even its own secret rules.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] It has since been reported that the NSA violated its own rules on data access thousands of times a year, many of these violations involving large-scale data interceptions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA has "generally disregarded the special rules for disseminating United States person information" by illegally sharing its intercepts with different law enforcement agencies.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Email contact lists (including those of US citizens) are collected at numerous foreign locations to work around the illegality of doing so on US soil.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Legal opinions on the NSA's bulk collection program have differed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Surely, such a program infringes on 'that degree of privacy' that the Founders enshrined in the Fourth Amendment.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] District Judge William Pauley ruled that the NSA's collection of telephone records is legal and valuable in the fight against terrorism.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In his opinion, he wrote, "a bulk telephony metadata collection program [is] a wide net that could find and isolate gossamer contacts among suspected terrorists in an ocean of seemingly disconnected data" and noted that a similar collection of data before 9/11 might have prevented the attack.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] At a March 2013 Senate Intelligence Committee hearing, Senator Ron Wyden asked the Director of National Intelligence James Clapper, "Does the NSA collect any type of data at all on millions or hundreds of millions of Americans?" Clapper replied "No, sir. ...
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] On July 31 NSA Deputy Director John Inglis conceded to the Senate that these intercepts had not been vital in stopping any terrorist attacks, but were "close" to vital in identifying and convicting four San Diego men for sending US$8,930 to Al-Shabaab, a militia that conducts terrorism in Somalia.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The U.S. government has aggressively sought to dismiss and challenge Fourth Amendment cases raised against it, and has granted retroactive immunity to ISPs and telecoms participating in domestic surveillance.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The U.S. military has acknowledged blocking access to parts of *The Guardian* website for thousands of defense personnel across the country, and blocking the entire *Guardian* website for personnel stationed throughout Afghanistan, the Middle East, and South Asia.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In October 2014, the United Nations report condemned mass surveillance programs carried out by the U.S. intelligence communities and other nations as violating multiple global treaties and conventions that guaranteed core privacy rights.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] An exploit dubbed EternalBlue, created by the NSA, was used in the WannaCry ransomware attack in May 2017.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The exploit had been leaked online by a hacking group, The Shadow Brokers, nearly a month before the attack.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Several experts have pointed the finger at the NSA's non-disclosure of the underlying vulnerability, and their loss of control over the EternalBlue attack tool that exploited it.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Edward Snowden said that if the NSA had "privately disclosed the flaw used to attack hospitals when they found it, not when they lost it, [the attack] might not have happened".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Former employee David Evenden, who had left the NSA to work for US defense contractor Cyperpoint at a position in the United Arab Emirates, was tasked with hacking UAE neighbor Qatar in 2015 to determine if they were funding terrorist group Muslim Brotherhood.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] He quit the company after learning his team had hacked Qatari Sheikha Moza bint Nasser's email exchanges with Michelle Obama, just before she visited Doha.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] Upon Evenden's return to the US, he reported his experiences to the FBI.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] The incident highlights a growing trend of former NSA employees and contractors leaving the agency to start up their firms, and then hiring out to countries like Turkey, Sudan, and even Russia, a country involved in numerous cyberattacks against the US.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] In May 2021, it was reported that the Danish Defence Intelligence Service collaborated with the NSA to wiretap on fellow EU members and leaders, leading to wide backlash among EU countries and demands for explanation from Danish and American governments.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/national-security-agency-p02] NSA director Paul Nakasone disclosed in a letter to Representative Ron Wyden that the NSA buys data without a warrant.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Although the process is specific to the object on which it is being performed, all reverse engineering processes consist of three basic steps: information extraction, modeling, and review.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Information extraction is the practice of gathering all relevant information for performing the operation.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Modeling is the practice of combining the gathered information into an abstract model, which can be used as a guide for designing the new object or system.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Review is the testing of the model to ensure the validity of the chosen abstract.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is applicable in the fields of computer engineering, mechanical engineering, design, electrical and electronic engineering, civil engineering, nuclear engineering, aerospace engineering, software engineering, chemical engineering, systems biology and more.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] There are many reasons for performing reverse engineering in various fields.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering has its origins in the analysis of hardware for commercial or military advantage.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] However, the reverse engineering process may not always be concerned with creating a copy or changing the artifact in some way.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] It may be used as part of an analysis to deduce design features from products with little or no additional knowledge about the procedures involved in their original production.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In some cases, the goal of the reverse engineering process can simply be a redocumentation of legacy systems.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Even when the reverse-engineered product is that of a competitor, the goal may not be to copy it but to perform competitor analysis.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Software reverse engineering can help to improve the understanding of the underlying source code for the maintenance and improvement of the software.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Relevant information can be extracted to make a decision for software development and graphical representations of the code can provide alternate views regarding the source code, which can help to detect and fix a software bug or vulnerability.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Frequently, as some software develops, its design information and improvements are often lost over time, but that lost information can usually be recovered with reverse engineering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The process can also help to cut down the time required to understand the source code, thus reducing the overall cost of the software development.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering can also help to detect and to eliminate a malicious code written to the software with better code detectors.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reversing a source code can be used to find alternate uses of the source code, such as detecting the unauthorized replication of the source code where it was not intended to be used, or revealing how a competitor's product was built.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] That process is commonly used for "cracking" software and media to remove their copy protection, or to create a possibly improved copy or even a knockoff, which is usually the goal of a competitor or a hacker.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Malware developers often use reverse engineering techniques to find vulnerabilities in an operating system to build a computer virus that can exploit the system vulnerabilities.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is also being used in cryptanalysis to find vulnerabilities in substitution cipher, symmetric-key algorithm or public-key cryptography.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] As computer-aided design (CAD) has become more popular, reverse engineering has become a viable method to create a 3D virtual model of an existing physical part for use in 3D CAD, CAM, CAE, or other software.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The reverse-engineering process involves measuring an object and then reconstructing it as a 3D model.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The physical object can be measured using 3D scanning technologies like CMMs, laser scanners, structured light digitizers, or industrial CT scanning (computed tomography).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The measured data alone, usually represented as a point cloud, lacks topological information and design intent.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The former may be recovered by converting the point cloud to a triangular-faced mesh.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering aims to go beyond producing such a mesh and to recover the design intent in terms of simple analytical surfaces where appropriate (planes, cylinders, etc.) as well as possibly NURBS surfaces to produce a boundary-representation CAD model.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Recovery of such a model allows a design to be modified to meet new requirements, a manufacturing plan to be generated, etc.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Hybrid modeling is a commonly used term when NURBS and parametric modeling are implemented together.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Using a combination of geometric and freeform surfaces can provide a powerful method of 3D modeling.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Areas of freeform data can be combined with exact geometric surfaces to create a hybrid model.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] A typical example of this would be the reverse engineering of a cylinder head, which includes freeform cast features, such as water jackets and high-tolerance machined areas.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is also used by businesses to bring existing physical geometry into digital product development environments, to make a digital 3D record of their own products, or to assess competitors' products.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] It is used to analyze how a product works, what it does, what components it has; estimate costs; identify potential patent infringement; etc.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Value engineering, a related activity that is also used by businesses, involves deconstructing and analyzing products.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] However, the objective is to find opportunities for cost-cutting.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of printed circuit boards involves recreating fabrication data for a particular circuit board.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] This is done primarily to identify a design, and learn the functional and structural characteristics of a design.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] It also allows for the discovery of the design principles behind a product, especially if this design information is not easily available.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Outdated PCBs are often subject to reverse engineering, especially when they perform highly critical functions such as powering machinery, or other electronic components.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering these old parts can allow the reconstruction of the PCB if it performs some crucial task, as well as finding alternatives which provide the same function, or in upgrading the old PCB.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering PCBs largely follow the same series of steps.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] First, images are created by drawing, scanning, or taking photographs of the PCB.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Then, these images are ported to suitable reverse engineering software in order to create a rudimentary design for the new PCB.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The quality of these images that is necessary for suitable reverse engineering is proportional to the complexity of the PCB itself.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] More complicated PCBs require well lighted photos on dark backgrounds, while fairly simple PCBs can be recreated simply with just basic dimensioning.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Each layer of the PCB is carefully recreated in the software with the intent of producing a final design as close to the initial.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Then, the schematics for the circuit are finally generated using an appropriate tool.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is a process of examination only, and the software system under consideration is not modified, which would otherwise be re-engineering or restructuring.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering can be performed from any stage of the product cycle, not necessarily from the functional end product.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] There are two components in reverse engineering: redocumentation and design recovery.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Redocumentation is the creation of new representation of the computer code so that it is easier to understand.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Meanwhile, design recovery is the use of deduction or reasoning from general knowledge or personal experience of the product to understand the product's functionality fully.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] It can also be seen as "going backwards through the development cycle".
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In this model, the output of the implementation phase (in source code form) is reverse-engineered back to the analysis phase, in an inversion of the traditional waterfall model.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Another term for this technique is program comprehension.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The Working Conference on Reverse Engineering (WCRE) has been held yearly to explore and expand the techniques of reverse engineering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Computer-aided software engineering (CASE) and automated code generation have contributed greatly in the field of reverse engineering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Software anti-tamper technology like obfuscation is used to deter both reverse engineering and re-engineering of proprietary software and software-powered systems.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In practice, two main types of reverse engineering emerge.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In the first case, source code is already available for the software, but higher-level aspects of the program, which are perhaps poorly documented or documented but no longer valid, are discovered.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In the second case, there is no source code available for the software, and any efforts towards discovering one possible source code for the software are regarded as reverse engineering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The second usage of the term is more familiar to most people.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of software can make use of the clean room design technique to avoid copyright infringement.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] On a related note, black box testing in software engineering has a lot in common with reverse engineering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The tester usually has the API but has the goals to find bugs and undocumented features by bashing the product from outside.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Binary reverse engineering is performed if source code for a software is unavailable.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] This process is sometimes termed *reverse code engineering*, or RCE.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] For example, decompilation of binaries for the Java platform can be accomplished by using Jad.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] One famous case of reverse engineering was the first non-IBM implementation of the PC BIOS, which launched the historic IBM PC compatible industry that has been the overwhelmingly-dominant computer hardware platform for many years.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of software is protected in the US by the fair use exception in copyright law.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The Wine project does the same thing for the Windows API, and OpenOffice.org is one party doing that for the Microsoft Office file formats.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of software can be accomplished by various methods.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Disassembly using a disassembler, meaning the raw machine language of the program is read and understood in its own terms, only with the aid of machine-language mnemonics.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] It works on any computer program but can take quite some time, especially for those who are not used to machine code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The Interactive Disassembler is a particularly popular tool.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Decompilation using a decompiler, a process that tries, with varying results, to recreate the source code in some high-level language for a program only available in machine code or bytecode.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Software classification is the process of identifying similarities between different software binaries (such as two different versions of the same binary) used to detect code relations between software samples.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The task was traditionally done manually for several reasons (such as patch analysis for vulnerability detection and copyright infringement), but it can now be done somewhat automatically for large numbers of samples.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] This method is being used mostly for long and thorough reverse engineering tasks (complete analysis of a complex algorithm or big piece of software).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In general, statistical classification is considered to be a hard problem, which is also true for software classification, and so few solutions/tools that handle this task well.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] A number of UML tools refer to the process of importing and analysing source code to generate UML diagrams as "reverse engineering" .
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Although UML is one approach in providing "reverse engineering" more recent advances in international standards activities have resulted in the development of the Knowledge Discovery Metamodel (KDM).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The standard delivers an ontology for the intermediate (or abstracted) representation of programming language constructs and their interrelationships.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] An Object Management Group standard (on its way to becoming an ISO standard as well), KDM has started to take hold in industry with the development of tools and analysis environments that can deliver the extraction and analysis of source, binary, and byte code.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] For source code analysis, KDM's granular standards' architecture enables the extraction of software system flows (data, control, and call maps), architectures, and business layer knowledge (rules, terms, and process).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The standard enables the use of a common data format (XMI) enabling the correlation of the various layers of system knowledge for either detailed analysis (such as root cause, impact) or derived analysis (such as business process extraction).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Although efforts to represent language constructs can be never-ending because of the number of languages, the continuous evolution of software languages, and the development of new languages, the standard does allow for the use of extensions to support the broad language set as well as evolution.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] KDM is compatible with UML, BPMN, RDF, and other standards enabling migration into other environments and thus leverage system knowledge for efforts such as software system transformation and enterprise business layer analysis.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Protocols are sets of rules that describe message formats and how messages are exchanged: the protocol state machine.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Accordingly, the problem of protocol reverse-engineering can be partitioned into two subproblems: message format and state-machine reverse-engineering.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The message formats have traditionally been reverse-engineered by a tedious manual process, which involved analysis of how protocol implementations process messages, but recent research proposed a number of automatic solutions.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Typically, the automatic approaches group observe messages into clusters by using various clustering analyses, or they emulate the protocol implementation tracing the message processing.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] There has been less work on reverse-engineering of state-machines of protocols.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In general, offline learning of small state-machines is known to be NP-complete, but online learning can be done in polynomial time.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] An automatic offline approach has been demonstrated by Comparetti et al. and an online approach by Cho et al.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Other components of typical protocols, like encryption and hash functions, can be reverse-engineered automatically as well.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Typically, the automatic approaches trace the execution of protocol implementations and try to detect buffers in memory holding unencrypted packets.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is an invasive and destructive form of analyzing a smart card.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The attacker uses chemicals to etch away layer after layer of the smart card and takes pictures with a scanning electron microscope (SEM).
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] That technique can reveal the complete hardware and software part of the smart card.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The major problem for the attacker is to bring everything into the right order to find out how everything works.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The makers of the card try to hide keys and operations by mixing up memory positions, such as by bus scrambling.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In some cases, it is even possible to attach a probe to measure voltages while the smart card is still operational.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The makers of the card employ sensors to detect and prevent that attack.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] That attack is not very common because it requires both a large investment in effort and special equipment that is generally available only to large chip manufacturers.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Furthermore, the payoff from this attack is low since other security techniques are often used such as shadow accounts.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] It is still uncertain whether attacks against chip-and-PIN cards to replicate encryption data and then to crack PINs would provide a cost-effective attack on multifactor authentication.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Full reverse engineering proceeds in several major steps.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] The first step after images have been taken with a SEM is stitching the images together, which is necessary because each layer cannot be captured by a single shot.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] A SEM needs to sweep across the area of the circuit and take several hundred images to cover the entire layer.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Image stitching takes as input several hundred pictures and outputs a single properly overlapped picture of the complete layer.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Next, the stitched layers need to be aligned because the sample, after etching, cannot be put into the exact same position relative to the SEM each time.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Therefore, the stitched versions will not overlap in the correct fashion, as on the real circuit.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Usually, three corresponding points are selected, and a transformation applied on the basis of that.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] To extract the circuit structure, the aligned, stitched images need to be segmented, which highlights the important circuitry and separates it from the uninteresting background and insulating materials.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Finally, the wires can be traced from one layer to the next, and the netlist of the circuit, which contains all of the circuit's information, can be reconstructed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is often used by people to copy other nations' technologies, devices, or information that have been obtained by regular troops in the fields or by intelligence operations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] It was often used during the Second World War and the Cold War.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering concepts have been applied to biology as well, specifically to the task of understanding the structure and function of gene regulatory networks.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] They regulate almost every aspect of biological behavior and allow cells to carry out physiological processes and responses to perturbations.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Understanding the structure and the dynamic behavior of gene networks is therefore one of the paramount challenges of systems biology, with immediate practical repercussions in several applications that are beyond basic research.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] There are several methods for reverse engineering gene regulatory networks by using molecular biology and data science methods.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Often, gene network reliability is tested by genetic perturbation experiments followed by dynamic modelling, based on the principle that removing one network node has predictable effects on the functioning of the remaining nodes of the network.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Applications of the reverse engineering of gene networks range from understanding mechanisms of plant physiology to the highlighting of new targets for anticancer therapy.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering applies primarily to gaining understanding of a process or artifact in which the manner of its construction, use, or internal processes has not been made clear by its creator.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Patented items do not of themselves have to be reverse-engineered to be studied, for the essence of a patent is that inventors provide a detailed public disclosure themselves, and in return receive legal protection of the invention that is involved.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] However, an item produced under one or more patents could also include other technology that is not patented and not disclosed.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Indeed, one common motivation of reverse engineering is to determine whether a competitor's product contains patent infringement or copyright infringement.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] In the United States, even if an artifact or process is protected by trade secrets, reverse-engineering the artifact or process is often lawful if it has been legitimately obtained.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Legal analysis has shown that reverse engineering may qualify as fair use when the intent is to study how a system functions, or conduct security research, assuming the copyright property is not redistributed Court rulings such as *Sega Enterprises Ltd. v.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Accolade, Inc.* have further clarified that reverse engineering to gain access to unprotected functional elements of software can be lawful under U.S. copyright doctrine.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of computer software often falls under both contract law as a breach of contract as well as any other relevant laws.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] That is because most end-user license agreements specifically prohibit it, and US courts have ruled that if such terms are present, they override the copyright law that expressly permits it (see *Bowers v.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] A limited exemption exists that allows the knowledge thus gained to be shared and used for interoperability purposes.
[src:reverse-engineering-ghidra/reverse-engineering] EU Directive 2009/24 on the legal protection of computer programs, which superseded an earlier (1991) directive, governs reverse engineering in countries of the European Union.
